[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'What if you could write an entire book in days, not months, without it reading like it was generated by a robot? Now, my name is Jason. I wrote 14 books the traditional way, and I worked at Kindlepreneur for 3 years, and after watching every AI writing method fail'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actual authors, I built a system that actually works. And that includes no shortcuts, and this is not a way to spam people. This is just a four-step process that harnesses your creativity and keeps'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your voice intact. So, let me show you exactly how that works. But before we get started, we need to talk about the tools that we need for this process. Now, there are a lot of tools out there, and most of them are just carbon copies'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of each other. There are a few that are designed specifically for writers who want to do creative writing, things like Sudowrite, Write Right, Novel Crafter, and I\'m even building my own Story'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Hacker tool that\'s developing now, but should be available by the time this video goes live. And all of these tools can absolutely simplify this process that I\'m going to show you, but I\'ve also found with the power that AI has these days, a simple chatbot can be'

[01:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'enough to actually do what I\'m going to demonstrate for you. You don\'t necessarily need fancy bells and whistles, although those can help. All you need is the right workflow, which is what we\'re going to get into right now.'

[01:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, there are four steps, and the first step is gathering ideas. And this is honestly my favorite step. I love the brainstorming process. I love putting the pieces together, because ultimately, writing a book is a lot like putting'

[01:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'together a puzzle. You have characters, you have locations and settings, you have plot details, you might have genres and tropes that you want to incorporate. This is actually one of the most'

[01:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'important things to do when you\'re gathering ideas is first determine your genre and your tropes. The reason for this is because if you want your book to have any chance of appealing to an audience, you have to know what that'

[01:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'audience wants. And typically in today\'s market, that is determined by the genre and the tropes that the books have. Often genres are just actual tropes that have become so popular that they\'ve just'

[02:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'been solidified into a genre. I like to use the whole idea of a container, and you\'ve probably heard this analogy before where if you try to dump a bunch of sand into a container and then put some big rocks into it, the rocks aren\'t'

[02:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to fit. But if you put the big rocks in first and then dump the sand into it, then you can fit everything into your jar. That\'s a lot how genre and tropes work. You want to get the genre and tropes established first, and'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then the sand, which is your own creativity, your own ideas, your own originality, can also fit in there with the genre and the tropes that you\'ve put in there, so that you end up with a story that is both appealing to readers,'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but also fresh and unique in your own way. So, that first step is figuring out what your genre is because that will fill in a lot of the holes that you already need for the gathering ideas process, and it leaves you with less'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stuff to do and makes it easier so you\'re not just dealing with a blank page. Now, I just want to make a quick shout-out because I\'ve been doing a lot of work on genre and inside of my Story Hacker membership, link below, you can'

[03:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually find a bunch of genre guides that I\'ve created, all of which are designed to help with this book writing process. And today, the one I\'m going to be showing off for you is the how to write cozy fantasy, which is what we\'re going to be talking about. I put a lot'

[03:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of these guys together, you can buy them on Amazon, but they are also free to members of the Story Hacker community. So far, I\'ve got 30 of them listed here, but I\'m making more every day. The goal is to have over 100 of these genre guides. So, today we\'re doing cozy'

[03:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fantasy. The way we\'re going to do this is inside of Claude Projects. To do this, you don\'t necessarily have to have a Claude subscription because Claude Projects is included on the free tier of Claude. However, if you are using the'

[03:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'free tier, it is unlikely that you\'re going to get very far before Claude throttles you, which is what it\'s known to do. Even on the paid plans, Claude is likely to throttle you, meaning that they will cut you off and make you wait'

[04:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'until you can use it again. But technically speaking, you can do everything I\'m going to show you inside of Claude even on the free plan. The first thing we\'re going to do is you want to create a project. So you can'

[04:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'create project. Now I would call it something like Novel Brainstormer. And then you create the project. And then you want to put a prompt into this. Now I\'ve actually already done this, so I\'m going to go ahead and delete this that we made. But mine looks like this.'

[04:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You\'ve got over here a set of instructions. You say edit instructions, and you will have this prompt. This right here is the prompt that you\'ll see in there, and I\'ll just go ahead and'

[04:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pause this. So you can pause the video and take a screenshot of this if you want. And I\'ll read this one out to you, but I\'m not going to read all of these prompts for obvious reasons. But basically it says, "You are an expert story brainstormer. It\'s your job to'

[04:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'collaborate with the user to brainstorm all the ingredients that they need for a novel. I want you to do a mix of asking questions of the user to get their thoughts and to probe for ideas they\'ve already had, as well as to offer your own suggestions when necessary, often'

[05:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'providing multiple suggestions for the user to pick from. By the end of your conversation, you should know all of the major details of the story, including the genre, the style, tone, the scale of the story, who the protagonist is, a list of all the characters in the novel,'

[05:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'any world building elements needed, and notes on what the opening image, inciting incident, midpoint, climax, and closing image of the story are. When you think you have all of these elements, ask the user if they want you you to put together a full dossier of their short'

[05:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'story together. If they say no, continue to work with them to establish the remaining details until they\'re ready. If they say yes, create a full summary of the novel based on the conversation you\'ve had. Include at the top of the dossier a logline that encapsulates the'

[05:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'story overall followed by a slightly larger synopsis with more details. Then make sure you have a brief list of all the characters, world-building elements, and the key plot points listed above. These should be in bulleted lists with'

[06:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'no more than one sentence for each element. So basically, the goal here is that we\'re going to be doing all of our brainstorming and at the end of this brainstorming session, it\'s going to summarize everything into a story dossier. So, that is the prompt that is'

[06:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pasted in here. So, we\'ll go ahead and save that. And now all you have to do is start a chat and begin talking to it about what you want. So, I\'m just going to start by saying, "I would like to'

[06:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'write a cozy fantasy novel." And that\'s enough to start with. And it says, "What a lovely project. Before we can dive into writing chapters, we\'ll need to build out the foundation. Let me ask you a few questions to to get started." Take your time. There are no wrong answers'

[06:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here. And then because Claude is getting more advanced these days, it actually gives me a bunch of questions. So, it says, "What is the heart of your story? Pick the vibe that feels closest. Cozy shop, a quiet mage or witch living in a small ordinary life, a found family in a'

[06:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fantastical cottage or village, or something else." We\'ll say a cozy shop. "What do you already have ready to share?" Nothing yet. Help me build it all. We\'ve done that. And so now it\'s continuing on. So now it\'s asking me, "What kind of shop or inn is it?" And we'

[07:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'could say, "Okay, bookshop inn at a crossroads between magical realms, an apothecary, tea shop." Let\'s say a bookshop. "Who\'s your main character? Is the owner, a newer arrival, an employee who slowly uncovers the shop\'s secret?"'

[07:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Let\'s say the owner. "What\'s the emotional core of the story?" How about rediscovering a lost passion or identity? And this process is just going to go on for a while. Now this is probably the longest step of this process, believe it or not, this is the'

[07:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'longest step because you want to take your time to make sure that the AI has all of your ideas down. Here\'s an interesting one. So, "Who is your main character broadly? A woman in her 30s or 40s, a man in his 30s or 40s, a young woman in her 20s, a young man in his'

[07:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '20s. You could also pencil in something here if your protagonist doesn\'t match any of those. We\'ll say a young elf in her 20s. Okay, so I could give it that one. What passion or identity did they'

[07:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lose? They used to be a writer but stopped. They were a mage or scholar who gave up their craft. They were an adventurer who walked away from that life. They were an artist. Let\'s say they were a mage. What tone do you want for the book overall? Whimsical and'

[08:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'light. Yes. Uh because this is a cozy fantasy. And so basically as you go through and ask it all of these questions, it will eventually feel like it has everything that it needs and it\'ll create a full dossier, which is'

[08:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what it\'s doing right now. Now, you can stop this and say, "Hey, no, I want to add more details." if you have more to offer, or you can just let it do its thing and it\'ll create the full story Bible for you. Now, keep in mind, this'

[08:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is not the fully fleshed out story Bible. We\'re going to do that in the next step, but this is kind of where we start, where we want a one sheet that has a list of everything that we need, all of the different assets that we need for the story. All right, and it is done'

[08:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with its story Bible. So, we have our main character, Eloen or Elo, and it\'s got this cool thing where I can tab through different things. It\'s outlined what the key points are. At this point,'

