VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can also download it as a file, an HTML file, but I\'m going to just copy that to the clipboard and save it. All right, so I\'ve now copied all of this into my document just under story dossier. We\'re going to need that for the next step.'

[09:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The next step is to create our story Bible. Now, the story dossier already has most of the elements that we need for the story Bible, but this next part is going to be split into three parts where we flesh out the characters, the'

[09:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'world building, and the outline because we need all three of those elements fully fleshed out before we can actually start writing the book. So, to help with that, I\'ve created three more projects. We\'ve got novel characters, novel world'

[09:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'building, and novel outliner. Let\'s start with characters first. This whole process is relatively simple. All we have to do is copy our story dossier and paste it in here, and it will automatically go. But, in case you want'

[09:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the prompt for it, of course, here it is. And once again, you can pause the video and take a screenshot of this if you want. But the basically all this does is it asks it to take the story dossier that I\'m about to give it and'

[10:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'create a fleshed out character sheet for all of the mentioned characters. And it\'ll include physical description, their role, their personality profiles, etc. And so, that\'s what we\'re going to do. So, I\'ve already pasted in the story'

[10:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dossier here. Here\'s my dossier, and let it go. And here it goes generating our characters. So, you can see we\'ve got a significantly more fleshed out version of our'

[10:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'character here, Eloin. Her physical description is tall and angular with a kind of posture that suggests she was once told to stand straight and forgot halfway through. Pale silver hair kept in a braid that starts neat and ends in'

[10:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'entropy. Forest green eyes that are sharper than she lets on. Ink stains on her fingers that survive soap water and apparent stubbornness. Dressed in dark practical layers. Nothing precious, nothing she\'d hesitate to ruin. And then it gives us her Myers-Briggs profile, as'

[10:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'well as her Enneagram and Clifton strengths, which is something I like to add in there to help the AI understand the character better. What\'s her core motivation? What\'s her background? What\'s a quirk or hobby that she\'s got?'

[11:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Because that can make these characters a little more three-dimensional. As as well as very important, her dialogue style. Dry and economical. She says the exact amount of words necessary and frequently uses the ones that create a'

[11:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'little distance. Deflects with practicality rather than deflects with humor. It\'s going through and doing this for all of of different characters. We\'ll let it finish. And once it\'s done, we can go ahead and copy this and go back to our document and paste it in'

[11:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here. So, we\'ll say character sheet, and then just paste that in. The reason I\'m saving these is cuz we\'re going to need them for later, particularly for the outlining and the chapter generation phase. But, before we get to that, we\'re'

[11:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just going to take the story dossier and repeat this process for world building. Let\'s go to our next project, which is novel world building. So, once again, all I have to do is paste in my story dossier and go. If you want to know the'

