[15:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'three of these. There was one other thing mentioned in these instructions, right? We had story dossier, character sheet, world building sheet, and plot template. So the plot template is a something that I strongly recommend. You don\'t necessarily have to do it for this'

[15:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'step, but I strongly recommend having a plot template as part of your process because that will give the AI something much more concrete to build off of. And bonus points if the plot template is'

[15:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tailored to the genre that you\'re writing in. Now I\'ve created a bunch of plot templates in my time. I created one that\'s sort of general called the plot module. I have a whole book on it that is a 40-chapter template that will work'

[16:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for pretty much almost all genres, particularly non-romance genres. But it so happens that in those genre guides I\'ve been developing, I create a plot template for each one of the genres. So'

[16:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that includes cozy fantasy, which is what this is. Here is the plot template for my cozy fantasy, and uh there are 26 chapters in this plot template. It looks something like this. Protagonist is'

[16:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'introduced in their current state of dissatisfaction, burnout, or disconnection from their true desires, often in a mundane or oppressive environment that highlights what is missing from their life. An unexpected catalyst arrives like a letter, an inheritance, an opportunity, or magical'

[16:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'encounter that offers a path towards something different. The protagonist experiences their first brush with the extraordinary they will enter, whether through a literal journey to a new location or the sudden appearance of magic in their ordinary life. Despite'

[16:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'initial hesitation or disbelief, something within the protagonist responds to this call, revealing a long-buried dream or desire. The chapter establishes the warm, comforting tone of the genre through sensory details and'

[17:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'atmospheric description while also demonstrating the protagonist\'s fundamental need for transformation and belonging. And then it has a couple of notes here like, what\'s the primary purpose of the scene? Is it multi-function? Is it doing multiple things like character development and'

[17:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'plot progression. What are some of the structural beats? And I also give it a rating. So, things like scene intensity, these are out of 10. Five. Spice level is one, meaning there\'s no spice whatsoever. Violence level, two.'

[17:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Swearing level, three. And so on. And I do this for each of the 26 chapters. So, all we\'re going to do is copy this template, go back to our novel outline your project, and say add files again, add text context, and call this plot'

[17:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'template. Paste all that in, say add context, and now we\'re we\'ve got all of the context that we want. And as you can see, we\'re still at only 1% of the project\'s capacity. So, we\'re good'

[17:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there. All we have to do now is just tell it to go. Say, write my outline, please. Always say please in case the robot overlords decides to take over. All right, so it has already started doing the outline here. It\'s It took a'

[18:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lot of time thinking about this before it got started. And as you can see, it\'s going through. It just started chapter four. If we go up and read the first chapter description here, "El arrives in Fern Hollow on a gray morning carrying'

[18:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one bag, a Mason jar notebook tucked inside a larger book about load-bearing walls, and the solicitor\'s letter she has read so many times its creases are soft. She has taken the inheritance not because she wanted it, but because she had nowhere else to be. The walk from'

[18:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the coaching inn to Wren Lane establishes Fern Hollow as a place that doesn\'t perform its magic. A baker\'s oven self-regulating and open window. The town square fountain faintly audible even at distance. Enchanted window boxes blooming in the wrong season. El notes'

[18:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all of this with the detached precision of someone trained to observe magic who has stopped caring about it. Marginalia\'s green door and brass book knocker are exactly as the solicitor\'s letter described. El lets herself in with a key. The moment she crosses the'

[18:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'threshold, the books begin reorganizing. A low rustle first, then a cascade. Volumes lifting from shelves and settling elsewhere, sorted by grief and longing and the particular ache of being somewhere new. She stands still in the middle of it. Footnotes appears on the'

[19:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'highest shelf and regards her without moving. Amber eyes already in possession of a verdict. Ella finds Sable\'s journal exactly where the accompanying letter said it would be, behind the front desk, tucked behind the wall in the back of the drawer. She picks it up, looks at'

[19:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it, and puts it down. She puts the kettle on instead. The chapter closes on her standing in the back room while the books arrange themselves in the shop beyond, drinking tea she made in someone else\'s kitchen, not yet ready to read the handwriting of a woman she met exactly twice. And the structural beat'

[19:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is this is the hook, the shop responding to her arrival, the inciting incident, and the first glimpse of a special world. So, as you can see, this definitely fits into the template that I read earlier, as well as pulls in all of'

