[23:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'validation and editing. Now, to a certain extent, you should be doing this as you go with the characters and the world-building sheet and the outline, but it\'s especially important here at the prose generation stage. For one,'

[23:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this is the best way to get your voice across is to make sure that it is matching your vision. But, also, the more you edit things and make it your own, the more of a case you have on copyright. Now, because in the United'

[24:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'States, anything that is AI-generated verbatim is not copyrightable, it\'s public domain. However, if you make significant edits to it and changes, you can still file for copyright and file'

[24:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for the human-written bits and for the selection and arrangement of AI text. So, the more you can do to make it your own, the better your case is to get copyright. So, I\'m going to show you a little bit of what that looks like for'

[24:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'me as I\'m going through these texts and validating them and editing them. You can also use tools like AutoCrit or ProWritingAid to help in your editing process as well, especially some of their line editing tools, and those will'

[24:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'give you suggestions which you can then manually input, which keeps you as the decision-maker and therefore the person responsible for the copyright of your edits. And then when we go back to generate chapter two, we\'ve already made'

[24:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a bunch of edits and it can see the edits that you make and kind of have an idea of what your style is. Plus it\'ll be able to read that chapter, know where you left off, and continue on with chapter two. And I\'ll show you that process once we\'ve gone through this.'

[25:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
